\description{
Build a publication-ready coefficient summary from one or more
fitted regression models. Beyond the standard \code{B} / \code{SE} / \code{CI} /
\code{p} columns, the same table layout supports \strong{standardised
coefficients} (\eqn{\beta}{beta}), \strong{average marginal effects}
(AME, with its own SE / \emph{p} / CI), \strong{partial effect sizes}
(\emph{\eqn{f^2}{f^2}} / \emph{\eqn{\eta^2}{eta^2}} / \emph{\eqn{\omega^2}{omega^2}}
for \code{lm}, partial \emph{\eqn{\chi^2}{chi-squared}} for \code{glm}),
\strong{pseudo-\eqn{R^2}{R^2}} for \code{glm}, and a wide vocabulary of
variance estimators (classical / HC* / cluster-robust with
Satterthwaite-corrected df / bootstrap / jackknife). Designed for
\strong{APA-strict} reporting in psychology, public health, sociology,
and biostatistics, with optional opt-in conventions for
econometrics and clinical trials.

Supports \code{lm} and \code{glm} (binomial / poisson / Gamma /
inverse.gaussian / quasi families with any link). Mixed-effects
models (\code{lmerMod}, \code{glmerMod}) are planned for spicy 0.16+.
}
\section{Vocabulary tokens}{
Three vector arguments — \code{show_columns}, \code{show_fit_stats}, and
\code{nested_stats} — accept named tokens that select \strong{what} to
display and in \strong{what order}. Tokens use snake_case (lowercase),
with capitalisation preserved only for canonical statistical
abbreviations (\code{AIC}, \code{BIC}, \code{F}, \code{LRT}, \code{B}, \code{SE}, \code{CI}, \code{AME}).
\subsection{\code{show_columns} — per-coefficient columns (in main table)}{

Estimate-related: \code{B}, \code{beta}, \code{SE}, \code{CI}, \code{t}, \code{p}.
Effect sizes (lm only): \code{partial_f2}, \code{partial_eta2},
\code{partial_omega2} (compact \code{value [CI]} rendering).
Effect sizes (glm only): \code{partial_chi2} — term-level partial
likelihood-ratio chi-square via \code{drop1(test = "LRT")}, the
generalised analog of the partial F-test (SAS PROC LOGISTIC
\code{TYPE3}; Long & Freese 2014 §3.5; Allison "TYPE3"). Compact
\code{value (df)} rendering; the df slot disambiguates factor terms
(k-1 df) from numeric terms (1 df).
Marginal effects: \code{AME}, \code{AME_p}, \code{AME_SE} (compact for \code{AME}).

Default: \code{c("B", "SE", "CI", "p")}.
If \code{standardized != "none"} and \code{"beta"} is not in \code{show_columns},
it is auto-injected after \code{B}. Asking for \code{"beta"} while
\code{standardized = "none"} raises \code{spicy_invalid_input}.
}

\subsection{\code{show_fit_stats} — model-level statistics (in footer)}{

Counts: \code{nobs}, \code{weighted_nobs}.
Variance explained (\code{lm} only): \code{r2}, \code{adj_r2}, \code{omega2}.
Pseudo-\eqn{R^2}{R^2} (\code{glm} only): \code{pseudo_r2_mcfadden} (McFadden 1974),
\code{pseudo_r2_nagelkerke} (Nagelkerke 1991),
\code{pseudo_r2_tjur} (Tjur 2009; binomial only).
Residual scale: \code{sigma} (lm \eqn{\hat{\sigma}}{sigma-hat} / glm dispersion), \code{rmse}.
Effect size: \code{f2}.
Information criteria: \code{AIC}, \code{AICc}, \code{BIC}, \code{deviance}.

Default is class-aware (resolved when \code{NULL}): for \code{lm},
\code{c("nobs", "r2", "adj_r2")}; for \code{glm},
\code{c("nobs", "pseudo_r2_mcfadden", "pseudo_r2_nagelkerke", "AIC")}.
}

\subsection{\code{nested_stats} — hierarchical comparison footer}{

Activates when \code{nested = TRUE}. Tokens: \code{r2_change},
\code{adj_r2_change}, \code{F}, \code{f2_change} (\code{lm} only), \code{LRT}, \code{AIC},
\code{AICc}, \code{BIC}, \code{deviance_change}, \code{p}.

Default is class-aware (resolved when \code{NULL}): for \code{lm}
hierarchies, \code{c("r2_change", "F", "p")} (APA hierarchical
regression standard); for \code{glm} hierarchies, \code{c("LRT", "p")}
(APA hierarchical-logistic standard; Hosmer & Lemeshow §3.5;
Long & Freese 2014 §3.6). Variance-explained tokens (\code{r2_change},
\code{adj_r2_change}, \code{F}, \code{f2_change}) are not defined for \code{glm} and
raise \code{spicy_invalid_input} if requested for an all-\code{glm}
hierarchy.
}
}

\section{Multi-model semantics}{
Pass a single \code{lm} fit or a \code{list()} of fits. A named list
(\code{list("Naive" = m1, "Adjusted" = m2)}) provides column headers
automatically; an unnamed list defaults to \code{"Model 1, 2, ..."}.
\code{model_labels} overrides both with explicit per-column labels.

For models with \strong{different response variables}, the DV name is
shown automatically in a header row (controllable via
\code{outcome_labels}). For models sharing the same DV, the DV is
mentioned in the table title only.
}

\section{Inference and standard errors}{
\code{vcov} selects the variance-covariance estimator: \code{"classical"}
(OLS), \code{"HC0"} to \code{"HC5"} (heteroskedasticity-consistent via
\code{\link[sandwich:vcovHC]{sandwich::vcovHC()}}), \code{"CR0"} to \code{"CR3"} (cluster-robust via
\code{\link[clubSandwich:vcovCR]{clubSandwich::vcovCR()}} with Satterthwaite-corrected df),
\code{"bootstrap"} (nonparametric or cluster bootstrap), or
\code{"jackknife"} (leave-one-out / leave-one-cluster-out).

For multi-model use, both \code{vcov} and \code{cluster} accept either a
single value (recycled to all models) \strong{or} a list (one per
model). The pedagogical use case \code{list(fit, fit, fit)} with
\code{vcov = list("classical", "HC3", "CR2")} enables side-by-side
SE-comparison in a single table.

Inferential regimes (B and AME share the same regime by design):
\itemize{
\item \code{classical}, \verb{HC*} → t with \code{df.residual}
\item \code{bootstrap}, \code{jackknife} → z asymptotic
\item \verb{CR0–CR3} → t with \strong{Satterthwaite-corrected df} (B via
\code{\link[clubSandwich:coef_test]{clubSandwich::coef_test()}}; AME via
\code{\link[clubSandwich:linear_contrast]{clubSandwich::linear_contrast()}} — see
Pustejovsky & Tipton 2018). spicy is the first R package to
offer AME-Satterthwaite under cluster-robust variance for
\code{lm}. For models with non-linear formulas (\code{poly()}, \code{I()},
\code{log()}, \code{splines::ns()}), AME inference falls back to
z-asymptotic with a \code{spicy_fallback} warning.
}
}

\section{Standardised coefficients}{
\code{standardized} controls the standardisation method when \code{"beta"}
is in \code{show_columns}:
\itemize{
\item \code{"refit"} — refit the model on z-scored predictors. For \code{lm},
the response is also z-scored (Cohen et al. 2003 gold standard);
for \code{glm}, the response stays on its observed scale and only
numeric predictors are standardised (Long & Freese 2014 §4.3.4
"x-standardization").
\item \code{"posthoc"} — post-hoc scaling. For \code{lm}:
\verb{\eqn{\beta}{beta} = B × SD(X) / SD(Y)}; for \code{glm}: X-only \verb{\eqn{\beta}{beta} = B × SD(X)} (the
response side is undefined on the link scale —
\code{parameters} / \code{effectsize} convention).
\item \code{"basic"} — like posthoc but factor-derived dummies are scaled
by their column SD (treated as numeric).
\item \code{"smart"} — Gelman (2008) recommendation: divide binary
predictors by \verb{2 × SD} instead of \code{SD}.
\item \code{"pseudo"} — \emph{glm only}. Menard (2004, 2011) fully-standardised
\verb{\eqn{\beta}{beta} = B × SD(X) / SD(Y*)}, where \verb{Y*} is the latent variable on
the link scale and
\verb{SD(Y*) = sqrt(var(\eqn{\hat{\eta}}{eta-hat}) + var_link)} with \code{var_link} =
\eqn{\pi}{pi}²/3 (logit), 1 (probit), \eqn{\pi}{pi}²/6 (cloglog). Defined for binomial
families; non-binomial returns NA with a \code{spicy_caveat}.
\item \code{"none"} (default) — no \eqn{\beta}{beta} computed.
}

For models with interactions or transformed predictors (\code{I()},
\code{poly()}, \code{log()}, \code{splines::ns()}), a \code{spicy_caveat} warning is
emitted reminding that standardised coefficients on such terms
should be interpreted with care (Cohen et al. 2003 §7.7;
Aiken & West 1991). The footer auto-documents the caveat.
}

\section{Hierarchical (nested) model comparison}{
Set \code{nested = TRUE} to add a footer block comparing each model
to the previous one. spicy validates that all models share
identical \code{nobs} AND identical response variable, raising
\code{spicy_invalid_input} otherwise (with a remediation snippet).

Class-aware default \code{nested_stats} for \code{lm}:
\code{c("r2_change", "F", "p")}. Customise via the \code{nested_stats}
argument with any combination of supported tokens.
}

\section{Output formats and broom integration}{
\code{output} selects the return type:
\itemize{
\item \code{"default"} — a \code{spicy_regression_table} object (a
\code{data.frame} subclass) printed via \code{\link[=spicy_print_table]{spicy_print_table()}}.
\item \code{"data.frame"} / \code{"long"} — raw data.frame / long-format
tibble (the underlying analytic representation).
\item \code{"gt"} / \code{"flextable"} / \code{"tinytable"} — rich-format HTML /
Word / PDF tables (requires the corresponding package).
\item \code{"excel"} — writes to \code{excel_path} via
\code{\link[openxlsx2:write_xlsx]{openxlsx2::write_xlsx()}} (returns \code{invisible(x)}).
\item \code{"clipboard"} — copies to system clipboard via
\code{\link[clipr:write_clip]{clipr::write_clip()}} (returns \code{invisible(x)}).
}

\code{\link[broom:tidy]{broom::tidy()}} returns a long tibble with one row per
\verb{(model_id, term, estimate_type)} and broom-canonical column
names (\code{estimate}, \code{std.error}, \code{conf.low}, \code{conf.high},
\code{statistic}, \code{p.value}). \code{\link[broom:glance]{broom::glance()}} returns one row per
model with the model-level statistics. \code{df.residual} is kept
numeric (not integer) so cluster-robust Satterthwaite df is
preserved verbatim.
}

\section{Output encoding}{
\code{table_regression()} produces UTF-8 output with Unicode
box-drawing for table layout and Greek / mathematical symbols
(\eqn{\beta}{beta}, \eqn{\omega^2}{omega^2}, \eqn{\chi^2}{chi-squared}, \eqn{f^2}{f^2}, \eqn{\Delta}{Delta}, †, em-dash). A UTF-8 capable terminal is
required (default in RStudio, R \eqn{\ge}{>=} 4.0 on Windows 10+, macOS,
modern Linux).
}

\section{Internationalisation}{
Output is in English. To localise visible text:
\itemize{
\item Use \code{reference_label}, \code{model_labels}, \code{outcome_labels},
and \code{labels} to override user-customisable strings.
\item For the title and footer, post-process the result via
\code{attr(result, "title") <- "..."} and
\code{attr(result, "note") <- "..."}.
}
}

\section{Weights}{
There is \strong{no} \code{weights} argument. Weights are a property of
the fitted model (extracted via \code{\link[stats:weights]{stats::weights()}}); pass them
when fitting:
\preformatted{
fit <- lm(y ~ x, data = df, weights = w)
table_regression(fit)
}
All downstream computations (vcov, AME, standardisation,
\code{weighted_nobs}) extract the weights automatically.
}

\section{Classed conditions}{

Every error and warning emitted by \code{table_regression()} carries
a classed condition for programmatic dispatch via \code{\link[=tryCatch]{tryCatch()}}
or \code{\link[=withCallingHandlers]{withCallingHandlers()}}. Errors inherit from \code{spicy_error}
(root); warnings from \code{spicy_warning}. Specific leaves used by
this function include \code{spicy_invalid_input},
\code{spicy_invalid_data}, \code{spicy_unsupported},
\code{spicy_missing_pkg}, \code{spicy_missing_column},
\code{spicy_ignored_arg}, \code{spicy_caveat}, \code{spicy_fallback}. See
\code{\link[=spicy-package]{spicy}} for the full taxonomy.
}

\examples{
\dontrun{
library(spicy)

# Single model, default APA layout
fit <- lm(wellbeing_score ~ age + sex + education,
          data = sochealth)
table_regression(fit)

# Hierarchical regression: nested = TRUE adds the comparison
# footer (\eqn{\Delta}{Delta}\eqn{R^2}{R^2}, partial F, p)
m1 <- lm(wellbeing_score ~ age, data = sochealth)
m2 <- lm(wellbeing_score ~ age + sex, data = sochealth)
m3 <- lm(wellbeing_score ~ age + sex + education,
         data = sochealth)
table_regression(
  list("Step 1" = m1, "Step 2" = m2, "Step 3" = m3),
  nested = TRUE
)

# Cluster-robust SEs with Satterthwaite df
fit_cl <- lm(wellbeing_score ~ age + sex,
             data = sochealth, weights = weight)
table_regression(
  fit_cl,
  vcov = "CR2",
  cluster = clinic_id
)

# Standardised coefficients (\eqn{\beta}{beta}) alongside B
table_regression(fit, standardized = "refit")

# Custom column set with AME displayed alongside its own p-value.
# `"p"` always refers to the B coefficient; for the AME-specific
# p-value use `"AME_p"`. Placing AME after the B p-value makes
# the "which p belongs to what" reading unambiguous.
table_regression(
  fit,
  show_columns = c("B", "p", "partial_f2", "AME", "AME_p")
)

# Pedagogical side-by-side SE comparison (same fit, three vcovs)
table_regression(
  list("Classical" = fit, "HC3" = fit, "CR2" = fit),
  vcov = list("classical", "HC3", "CR2"),
  cluster = list(NULL, NULL, sochealth$clinic_id)
)

# Output to gt
table_regression(fit, output = "gt")

# Tidy long format for downstream pipelines
broom::tidy(table_regression(fit))
}

}
\references{
APA Manual 7 (American Psychological Association, 2020),
Tables 7.13–7.15.

Aiken, L.S. & West, S.G. (1991). \emph{Multiple regression: Testing
and interpreting interactions}.

Cohen, J., Cohen, P., West, S.G., & Aiken, L.S. (2003).
\emph{Applied multiple regression / correlation analysis for the
behavioral sciences} (3rd ed.). Lawrence Erlbaum.

Pustejovsky, J.E. & Tipton, E. (2018). Small-sample methods for
cluster-robust variance estimation and hypothesis testing in
fixed effects models. \emph{Journal of Business & Economic
Statistics}, 36(4), 672–683.

Wasserstein, R.L., Schirm, A.L., & Lazar, N.A. (2019). Moving
to a world beyond "p < 0.05". \emph{The American Statistician},
73(sup1), 1–19.
}
